## DESCRIPTION
## Michigan precalculus gateway problem: topic solving linear systems
## ENDDESCRIPTION

DOCUMENT();
loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "PGchoicemacros.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

Context("Numeric");

## solution:
##   x + y = a,
##   d x - c y = e = ysol(c + d) + a d
##   so x = a - y
##   -(c + d) y + a d = ysol(c + d) + ad
##   -(c + d) y = ysol (c + d)
##   so y = -ysol

$y = random(1,7,1);  # the actual solution is y = -$y
$c = random(3,6,1);
$d = random(1,2,1);
$dd = ( $d == 1 ) ? '' : $d;

$rhs1 = $y*($c + $d);
$emin = ( $rhs1 > 5 ) ? $rhs1 - 5 : 1;
$emax = ( $rhs1 - 1 > 15 ) ? 15 : $rhs1 - 1;
$e1 = random($emin, $emax, 1);
$a = int(($rhs1 - $e1)/$d);
$e = $rhs1 + $a*$d;

$ysol = Compute( -1*$y );

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Suppose that \( x + y = $a \) and \( $dd x - $c y = $e \).
What is \(y\)?
$BR
\(y = \) \{ $ysol->ans_rule(10) \}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS( $ysol->cmp() );

$ad = $a*$d;
$cpd = $c + $d;
$ycd = $y*($c + $d);

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR SOLUTION $PAR

Note that we are solving for \(y\), so that it is useful to
eliminate \(x\) from the equations.  Solving for \(x\) in the
first equation, we have
\(x = $a - y\).
$PAR
Plugging into the second equation, we have
\[\begin{aligned}
    $dd($a - y) - $c y +  &= $e\\
    -$cpd y + $ad &= $e \\
    -$cpd y &= $rhs1.
\end{aligned}\]
Thus \( y = -$y\).

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

ENDDOCUMENT();
